                {
                  "key": "response",
                  "value": {
                    "stringValue": "Two ways to check it, from simplest to most thorough:\n\n**1. Run just Story A's unit tests:**\n```\npython -m pytest tests/test_consolidate.py -v\n```\n\n**2. Manual end-to-end check against the real sample data** (PowerShell):\n```powershell\npython -m extractor --input received --output extracted --state-dir .state_verify\npython -m extractor.consolidate --csv-path extracted/records.csv --output-path extracted/records_consolidated.csv\nGet-Content extracted/records_consolidated.csv\n```\n\nOr the bash equivalent:\n```bash\npython -m extractor --input received --output extracted --state-dir .state_verify\npython -m extractor.consolidate --csv-path extracted/records.csv --output-path extracted/records_consolidated.csv\ncat extracted/records_consolidated.csv\n```\n\nThe second command prints one summary line per consolidated group to stdout as it runs, and `records_consolidated.csv` will have one row per unbroken run of Model/Agent/Skills/JIRA Key — you should see far fewer rows than `records.csv` (I saw 80 raw rows collapse to 6 groups). Use a throwaway `--state-dir` (as above) if you don't want this to touch your real `.state/`; delete `.state_verify/` and the two CSVs afterward if this is just a smoke test."
                  },
